      <text xml:space="preserve">'''Cytology''' (from [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] {{lang|grc|κύτος}}, ''kytos'', &quot;a hollow&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|last=Kirkpatrick ''et al.''|title=The Cassell Concise English Dictionary|location=London|date=1989|pages=324|isbn=0-304-31806-X}}&lt;/ref&gt;; and {{lang|grc|-λογία}}, ''[[wiktionary:-logia|-logia]]'') means &quot;the study of [[cell (biology)|cell]]s&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{EMedicineDictionary|cytology}}&lt;/ref&gt;
Cytology is that branch of life science, which deals with the study of cells in terms of structure, function and chemistry. 
Based on usage it can refer to: 
*[[Cytopathology]]: the study of '''cellular''' disease and the use of cellular changes for the diagnosis of disease.
*[[Cell biology]]: the study of (normal) cellular [[anatomy]], function and [[chemistry]].

